<section xml:id="section-variation" >
<title>Variation</title>

<introduction>

<p>In <xref ref="section-rates" /> we compared data based on the rate. Here we will emphasize how one variable affects another.</p>

</introduction>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-vary-direct">
	<title>Direct Relations</title>

	<p>In <xref ref="section-rates" /> we saw examples where the data increased. For example the salaries went up each year. The quadratic (<xref ref="example-differences-quadratic" />) and exponential (<xref ref="example-differences-exponential" />) also are increasing data. When an increase in one variable causes another to increase, we call the relationship between them <term>direct</term>.</p>

	<p>For some problems it makes sense to look at these another way. Consider the situation in <xref ref="figure-hydraulic-press" />. The pressure exerted on a fluid by a piston is the ratio of the force exerted and the area of the piston. On the left that is <m>P=\frac{F_1}{A_1}</m>. The same is true on the right <m>P=\frac{F_2}{A_2}</m>. Because the hydraulic fluid is contiguous the pressure is the same on both sides. Thus <me>\frac{F_1}{A_1} = \frac{F_2}{A_2}</me>.</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-hydraulic-press">
		<caption>Hydraulic Press</caption>
		<image source="images/hydraulic-press" width="60%"/>
	</figure>

	<example xml:id="exmaple-hydraulic-piston-calculate">
		<statement><p>If the left piston has area <m>16 \text{ cm}^2</m>, and 5.0 N of force is exerted, what is the force exerted on the second piston if it has area <m>25 \text{ cm}^2</m>?</p></statement>
		<solution><p>Notice this is a proportion problem. We can use the relationship
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{16 \text{ cm}^2}{5.0 \text{ N}} \amp = \frac{25 \text{ cm}^2}{F_2}.</mrow>
				<mrow>(16 \text{ cm}^2)F_2 \amp = (25 \text{ cm}^2)(5.0 \text{ N}). \amp \text{ Eliminating the denominators.}</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{(16 \text{ cm}^2)F_2}{(16 \text{ cm}^2)} \amp = \frac{(25 \text{ cm}^2)(5.0 \text{ N})}{(16 \text{ cm}^2)}. </mrow>
				<mrow>F_2 \amp \approx 7.8 \text{ N}.</mrow>
			</md></p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<p>Next lets consider how changing the size of the second piston affects the force.</p>

	<example xml:id="example-hydraulic-piston-change">
		<statement><p>If the second piston's area is change from <m>25 \text{ cm}^2</m> to <m>36 \text{ cm}^2</m>, what is the increase or decrease in force?</p></statement>
		<solution><p>First we setup the same problem as in <xref ref="exmaple-hydraulic-piston-calculate" />
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{16 \text{ cm}^2}{5.0 \text{ N}} \amp = \frac{36 \text{ cm}^2}{F_2}.</mrow>
				<mrow>(16 \text{ cm}^2)F_2 \amp = (36 \text{ cm}^2)(5.0 \text{ N}). \amp \text{ Eliminating the denominators.}</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{(16 \text{ cm}^2)F_2}{(16 \text{ cm}^2)} \amp = \frac{(36 \text{ cm}^2)(5.0 \text{ N})}{(16 \text{ cm}^2)}. </mrow>
				<mrow>F_2 \amp \approx 11 \text{ N}.</mrow>
			</md></p>
			<p>The piston is larger and the force is also larger</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<example xml:id="example-voltage-resistance-linear">
		<statement><p>Voltage and resistance vary directly (see further <xref ref="example-vary-ohm" />) . If voltage is 24 V and resistance is <m>8 \Omega</m>, how would the voltage have to change if the resistance changes to <m>6 \Omega</m>? to <m>10 \Omega</m>?</p></statement>
		<solution><p>Because the relationship is direct we can write
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{V_1}{R_1} \amp = \frac{V_2}{R_2}.</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{24 \text{ V}}{8 \Omega} \amp = \frac{V_2}{6 \Omega}.</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{24 \text{ V}}{8 \Omega}(6 \Omega) \amp = V_2. \amp \text{ Eliminating the denominator on the right}</mrow>
				<mrow>18 \text{ V} \amp = V_2.</mrow>
			</md>
			We do the same for the second case.
			<md>
				<mrow>\frac{V_1}{R_1} \amp = \frac{V_2}{R_2}.</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{24 \text{ V}}{8 \Omega} \amp = \frac{V_2}{10 \Omega}.</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{24 \text{ V}}{8 \Omega}(10 \Omega) \amp = V_2. \amp \text{ Eliminating the denominator on the right}</mrow>
				<mrow>30 \text{ V} \amp = V_2.</mrow>
			</md>
			Notice that the resistances we chose change in a linear fashion: 6, 8, 10. Also note that the voltages changed in a linear fashion: 18, 24, 30.</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-vary-inverse">
	<title>Inverse Relations</title>

	<p>In <xref ref="example-vary-ohm" /> we saw data where the increase in one variable caused a decrease in the other. That example is known as an <term>inverse</term> relation.</p>

	<p>Whereas a direct relation can be expressed as <m>\frac{V_1}{R_1} = \frac{V_2}{R_2}</m> inverse relation can be expressed as <m>I_1 R_1 = I_2 R_2</m>.</p>

	<example xml:id="example-current-resistance">
		<statement><p>If the current is 3 amps when the resistance is 8 Ohms, what will the current be when the resistance is 6 Ohms? 4 Ohms?</p></statement>
		<solution><p>Because this is an inverse relation, we can write
			<md>
				<mrow>I_1 R_1 \amp = I_2 R_2</mrow>
				<mrow>(3 \text{ amps})(8 \Omega) \amp I_2(6 \Omega)</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{(3 \text{ amps})(8 \Omega)}{6 \Omega} \amp I_2 \amp \text{ Eliminating the denominator on the right}</mrow>
				<mrow>2.25 \text{ amps} \amp = I_2.</mrow>
			</md>
			The second case can be written
			<md>
				<mrow>(3 \text{ amps})(8 \Omega) \amp I_2(4 \Omega)</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{(3 \text{ amps})(8 \Omega)}{4 \Omega} \amp I_2 \amp \text{ Eliminating the denominator on the right}</mrow>
				<mrow>1.5 \text{ amps} \amp = I_2.</mrow>
			</md>
		</p></solution>
	</example>

	<p>Note that the relation in <xref ref="example-current-resistance" /> the resistances we chose change in a linear fashion: 4, 6, 8. The current also change in a linear fashion: 3, 2.25, 1.5. Thus the relation is inverse linear.</p>

	<example xml:id="example-inverse-exponential">
		<title>Decreasing Exponential</title>

		<statement><p>In <xref ref="table-inverse-exponential" /> we see data for an exponential with a negative exponent. Note that this decreases. The differences display the same pattern of matching the data except they are negative. The negative should make sense because the data is decreasing. This is inverse exponential.</p></statement>
	</example>

	<table xml:id="table-inverse-exponential">
		<title>Negative Exponential</title>

		<tabular>
			<row><cell><m>n</m></cell> <cell><m>2^{-n}</m></cell> <cell>Difference</cell> </row>
			<row><cell>1</cell> <cell>1/2</cell> </row>
			<row><cell>2</cell> <cell>1/4</cell> <cell>-1/4</cell> </row>
			<row><cell>3</cell> <cell>1/8</cell> <cell>-1/8</cell> </row>
			<row><cell>4</cell> <cell>1/16</cell> <cell>-1/16</cell> </row>
